The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have been discussing the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world where more people mean less food, where increasing resource demand leads to depletion and war, and where the growing production capacity of the past decades results in more pollution and global warming.
One of the sacred texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits of Growth, still influences the environmental movement today.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything will get better – human health, standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
They are seen by their opponents as the "economists of abundance" who trust the market, which allegedly solves all problems.
But instead of picking facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see if the world is really getting better or worse.
I have tried to achieve this together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing a value list for the past 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender ratio, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists have all answered the same question: What were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including predictions up to 2050.
Based on classical economic evaluations of all factors from mortality rates, health damage, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands and higher hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the extent of the problem, it is compared to its solution with the total available resources.
As a result, the size of the problem becomes clear as a percentage of the GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's consider the gender inequality.
Essentially, we had almost half of the world's population excluded from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the world's workforce were female.
What are the losses that arose from this low percentage?
Even considering the higher costs due to women's education and the unpaid domestic work that someone must do, the losses were at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female workforce participation rate and smaller income disparities, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It will probably be very surprising that climate change is likely to bring a growing net benefit from 1900 to 2025 – which will increase to annually 1.5% of the GDP.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs moderately, the benefits will outweigh the costs.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 inputs were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect worth 0.8% of the GDP.
Similarly, moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of the GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs about 0.2% of the GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, resulting in a loss of about 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, costs increase and benefits decrease, dramatically lowering the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs, justifying cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the valuation list also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by hazardous fumes from cooking and heating, resulting in a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in 1900, these costs were 19% of the GDP, and it is expected to decrease to 1% by 2050.
Most health indicators have improved worldwide.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy had changed very little.
The size of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and likely to be 76 years by 2050).
The greatest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
As recently as 1970, for example, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved in the entire 20th century by world peace.
This success has many parents.
The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and have promised another 10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, the cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the 20th century were an astonishing 32% of the world's GDP.
Today they have decreased to about 11% and will halve again by 2050.
Although optimists may not be right in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the 20th century probably costs about 1% of the GDP annually, and much more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of the GDP.
And the overall trend is even clearer.
Relative to the resources available to combat them, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no problems anymore.
Although they have decreased in the areas of health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
However, realists should gradually get used to the idea that the world has improved significantly.
Furthermore, the valuation list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not align our view of the future with the scariest stories or the loudest interest groups, but with objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
